7434576930965794816,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/sachigupta12_jack-dorsey-just-fired-4000-people-and-replaced-activity-7434576930965794816-j5e6,jack dorsey just fired 4,000 people and replaced them with AI. block's stock jumped 24%. and honestly? i'm not surprised. here's how i look at it. AI doesn't get tired. it doesn't need three… | Sachi Gupta,https://in.linkedin.com/in/sachigupta12?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image,sachigupta12,jack dorsey just fired 4,000 people and replaced them with AI.,51,jack dorsey just fired 4,000 people and replaced them with AI. block's stock jumped 24%. and honestly? i'm not surprised. here's how i look at it. AI doesn't get tired. it doesn't need three follow ups to finish a task. it just does the work. faster. over and over again. that's why headcount is shrinking. not because people aren't talented. but because a huge chunk of what most teams do every day is REPETITIVE. dorsey proved it publicly. others are doing it quietly. we see this every week with the teams we work with at thinklylabs. the ones actually getting ROI from AI have two things figured out 1. adding ai to operational repetitive tasks. 2. designing for multiplication, not replacement. the founders still debating whether AI is overhyped are going to feel this the hard way. faster output. same results. smaller teams. this is just the beginning. before you go chasing the next AI tool, just map out where your team is losing time to work that repeats itself. that's your starting point.,post,2026-03-05T06:51:51.121Z,163,2026-03-03T12:34:28.086Z,Person,0,0,jack dorsey just fired 4,000 people and replaced them with AI.<br/><br/>block&apos;s stock jumped 24%.<br/><br/>and honestly? i&apos;m not surprised.<br/><br/>here&apos;s how i look at it.<br/>AI doesn&apos;t get tired. it doesn&apos;t need three follow ups to finish a task.<br/>it just does the work. faster. over and over again.<br/><br/>that&apos;s why headcount is shrinking. not because people aren&apos;t talented. <br/>but because a huge chunk of what most teams do every day is REPETITIVE.<br/><br/>dorsey proved it publicly. others are doing it quietly.<br/><br/>we see this every week with the teams we work with at thinklylabs.<br/><br/>the ones actually getting ROI from AI have two things figured out <br/>1. adding ai to operational repetitive tasks.<br/>2. designing for multiplication, not replacement.<br/><br/>the founders still debating whether AI is overhyped are going to feel this the hard way.<br/>faster output. same results. smaller teams.<br/>this is just the beginning.<br/><br/>before you go chasing the next AI tool, just map out where your team is losing time to work that repeats itself.<br/><br/>that&apos;s your starting point.,12376,,500,,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5603AQGIQukCW_UPeg/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B56ZxwfdaCJAAg-/0/1771413825141?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=DSWavBa-vWSv13YRJ0vodueTryuTNeCXk3FgJCmfLEA
7433210837164580864,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/audrey-chen-tech_few-weeks-before-clawdbot-i-had-built-a-simple-activity-7433210837164580864-Yvmo,few weeks before clawdbot i had built a simple jarvis (jiavis) for home automation by running phi-2 locally 24/7 on an intel asus nuc 14 rvk + speaker & microphone one file, open source as always:… | Jia C | 29 comments,https://www.linkedin.com/in/audrey-chen-tech,audrey-chen-tech,few weeks before clawdbot i had built a simple jarvis (jiavis) for home automation,199,few weeks before clawdbot i had built a simple jarvis (jiavis) for home automation by running phi-2 locally 24/7 on an intel asus nuc 14 rvk + speaker & microphone one file, open source as always: https://lnkd.in/gx_P4mnJ,post,2026-03-05T06:51:51.163Z,323,2026-02-27T18:06:05.937Z,Person,29,0,few weeks before clawdbot i had built a simple jarvis (jiavis) for home automation <br/><br/>by running phi-2 locally 24/7 on an intel asus nuc 14 rvk + speaker &amp; microphone<br/><br/>one file, open source as always:<br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fgx_P4mnJ&amp;urlhash=aXmy&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/gx_P4mnJ</a>,47729,49,500,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5605AQE_xe8X45ZrtA/videocover-high/B56ZygR0pKKUBY-/0/1772215555046?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=k1pru0vhIDB6KrbBGiOWMhqNwf8PFjJtZw3Gb4btUyg,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5603AQGDEHwcSAsPug/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B56Zu4RiMoG0Ag-/0/1768323163646?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=eLdgkouOcici2UYOUcBx7eoKUthdogurLqSjdGEj4uE
7432636058644692992,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/oncelozgul_we-track-one-kpi-at-patientdeskai-yc-w26-activity-7432636058644692992-vTSc,We track one KPI at Patientdesk.ai (YC W26). Revenue. Everything else is noise. Tonight Paul Graham spoke at Y Combinator's office in Mountain View. He said 10% week over week growth is awesome… | Oncel Ozgul,https://www.linkedin.com/in/oncelozgul?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image,oncelozgul,We track one KPI at Patientdesk.ai (YC W26).,63,We track one KPI at Patientdesk.ai (YC W26) . Revenue. Everything else is noise. Tonight Paul Graham spoke at Y Combinator 's office in Mountain View. He said 10% week over week growth is awesome. He's right. Most companies never get close. But we're challenging ourselves to >15%. Not because 10% isn't enough. Because the only way to find your ceiling is to keep raising the bar. Who else is pushing past 10%?,post,2026-03-05T06:51:51.618Z,105,2026-02-26T04:02:08.064Z,Person,6,0,We track one KPI at <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/patientdesk-ai?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Patientdesk.ai (YC W26)</a>. Revenue. Everything else is noise.<br/><br/>Tonight Paul Graham spoke at <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/school/y-combinator/?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Y Combinator</a>&apos;s office in Mountain View. He said 10% week over week growth is awesome. <br/><br/>He&apos;s right. Most companies never get close.<br/><br/>But we&apos;re challenging ourselves to &gt;15%.<br/><br/>Not because 10% isn&apos;t enough. Because the only way to find your ceiling is to keep raising the bar.<br/><br/>Who else is pushing past 10%?,1776,,500,,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5603AQHyVNHhesYvew/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B56ZxGvRd0KUAg-/0/1770713324910?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=R1F9j4-Z7r2IjnC0xgpyTintVQ8l3WnawDP_up3ex84
7435036886823424001,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/devansh-raulo-4337a71b1_excited-to-announce-i-lost-the-csi-spit-hackathon-activity-7435036886823424001-6wmK,Excited to announce I lost the CSI-SPIT hackathon recently 🥳 , and within a week I was shamelessly at Veermata Jijabai Technological Institute (VJTI) for another (hackathon). Fun part is first… | Devansh Raulo | 18 comments,https://in.linkedin.com/in/devansh-raulo-4337a71b1?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image,devansh-raulo-4337a71b1,Excited to announce I lost the CSI-SPIT hackathon recently 🥳 , and within a week I was shamelessly at Veermata Jijabai Technological Institute (VJTI) for another (hackathon).,182,Excited to announce I lost the CSI-SPIT hackathon recently 🥳 , and within a week I was shamelessly at Veermata Jijabai Technological Institute (VJTI) for another (hackathon). Fun part is first. Tech part is below the fun part of this post. As always, during the month end, I face a scarcity of GitHub CoPilot credits, so I started coding on second day of the hackathon at 5:30 am (limits resetted at March 1st) 🫠 . What did I do until that?? Harsh , ujjjwal and me roamed and roamed around the campus, it's what you do at a hackathon. When we returned, we saw Sachin sir brainstorming with our peers. We were feeling pretty confident 💪 , thanks to four cans of Red Bull which the organizers graciously provided, and approached him with our ideas which we discussed till late night. This is where we met new friends Joel , Shashank , Dhruv and many (I don't have their Linkedins) others who were in for fun. Until 5:30, we talked, shared experiences (sage advice from my seniors) and laughed like mad 😁 . I was half sure if it wasn't for Bharat sir being chill, we would have been removed from the campus. Before pitching round, we all were test subjects of Joel and Shashank 's project. Theirs was a missile detection and citizens evacuation system, where for demo, the missile (a Red Bull can) was thrown at the guy shooting the video (me) 🤕 . It was a good project, but I still don't appreciate being hit. Now let's come to the tech part. M-Indicator AI hackathon was the name, and hence my pea sized brain decided to integrate AI to the already crazy M-Indicator app. I would have loved to share the source code, but I hope you would directly view it in your app. Well, the AI turned which I added were: 1. Custom RAPTOR algo on M-Indicator's transit data which suggests trains depending on user's behaviour with explainable AI. 2. Various gaussian, bayesian and regression models for calculating seating probability (whether your legs would hurt), friction commute (add shoulders hurting too) etc. and many more. 3. Meetup Scheduling with friends. I used (I can neither pronounce it or understand it yet) a Wasserstein-2 barycenter optimisation over Gaussian arrival distributions. I had a coarse logic which worked quite well but this equation worked better than anything.. so yeah I vibecoded this. Dhruv conveniently spotted my algos calculated the shortest travel time but not the fastest arrival time possible when pitching had already started. Needless to say, I had to start from scratch and was the third last person to pitch ( Harsh and Joel were the next 2, frankly because we were busy having fun). When the winners were announced, me, Dhruv , Joel and Shashank were overjoyed to find we were winners (40k didn't hurt). Frankly, everyone seated there had fantastic projects, we had a good fortune going Thank you Sachin sir, Amal sir and Mahesh sir for being awesome and considering me worthy 🙏 . If you ever see me at a hackathon, please network with me 😊 Devansh Raulo,post,2026-03-05T06:51:51.923Z,12,2026-03-04T19:02:10.093Z,Person,18,0,Excited to announce I lost the <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/company/s-p-i-t-csi?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>CSI-SPIT</a> hackathon recently 🥳 , and within a week I was shamelessly at <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/school/veermata-jijabai-technological-institute/?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Veermata Jijabai Technological Institute (VJTI)</a> for another (hackathon).<br/><br/>Fun part is first. Tech part is below the fun part of this post.<br/><br/>As always, during the month end, I face a scarcity of <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/github?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>GitHub</a> CoPilot credits, so I started coding on second day of the hackathon at 5:30 am (limits resetted at March 1st) 🫠 . What did I do until that?? <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/harsh-jain-82243128b?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Harsh</a>, <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/ujjjwal-warade-736b452b5?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>ujjjwal</a> and me roamed and roamed around the campus, it&apos;s what you do at a hackathon. When we returned, we saw <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/sachin-teke-314213b3?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Sachin</a> sir brainstorming with our peers. We were feeling pretty confident 💪 , thanks to four cans of <a class="link" href="https://at.linkedin.com/company/red-bull?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Red Bull</a> which the organizers graciously provided, and approached him with our ideas which we discussed till late night. <br/><br/>This is where we met new friends <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/joel-pawar?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-nam