7432497725432070144,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/uzair-javaid_when-anthropic-starts-talking-distillation-activity-7432497725432070144-_vMH,Anthropic Discusses AI Policy with Bloomberg | Uzair Javaid, Ph.D. posted on the topic | LinkedIn,https://sg.linkedin.com/in/uzair-javaid,uzair-javaid,When Anthropic starts talking Distillation Attacks & AI Policy, Bloomberg makes the call.,126,When Anthropic starts talking Distillation Attacks & AI Policy, Bloomberg makes the call. Guess who answers? I joined Insights with Haslinda Amin on Bloomberg this week to break down the AI race, IP theft, and why data quality—not just model size—is the real "secret sauce" for a competitive edge. Watch the session here (1:20:00 mark): https://lnkd.in/dS7jMBJ3 Thanks Naman Tandon & Haslinda Amin for having me!,post,2026-03-05T06:51:52.587Z,216,2026-02-25T18:52:26.855Z,Person,5,0,When <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/anthropicresearch?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Anthropic</a> starts talking Distillation Attacks &amp; AI Policy, <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/bloomberg?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Bloomberg</a> makes the call. Guess who answers?<br/><br/>I joined Insights with Haslinda Amin on Bloomberg this week to break down the AI race, IP theft, and why data quality—not just model size—is the real &quot;secret sauce&quot; for a competitive edge.<br/><br/>Watch the session here (1:20:00 mark): <br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FdS7jMBJ3&amp;urlhash=3EkH&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/dS7jMBJ3</a><br/><br/>Thanks <a class="link" href="https://hk.linkedin.com/in/naman-tandon-83b6566a?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Naman Tandon</a> &amp; <a class="link" href="https://sg.linkedin.com/in/haslinda-amin-0a29892b?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Haslinda Amin</a> for having me!,5353,,500,,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5603AQHT96uRCo8S1A/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B56ZyYj36hHgAg-/0/1772086067687?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=6NPt0uzJisKMnRhr9DaEwZbKDpzb7adoYri2t_ZtQXg
7431602929305825280,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/vaidehi-shah-47901727a_%F0%9D%97%94-%F0%9D%98%81%F0%9D%97%BF%F0%9D%98%82%F0%9D%97%B9%F0%9D%98%86-%F0%9D%98%84%F0%9D%97%B5%F0%9D%97%BC%F0%9D%97%B9%F0%9D%97%B2%F0%9D%98%80%F0%9D%97%BC%F0%9D%97%BA%F0%9D%97%B2-%F0%9D%97%A1%F0%9D%97%9A%F0%9D%97%A2-%F0%9D%97%B6%F0%9D%97%BB%F0%9D%98%81%F0%9D%97%B2%F0%9D%97%BF%F0%9D%97%BB%F0%9D%98%80%F0%9D%97%B5%F0%9D%97%B6%F0%9D%97%BD-activity-7431602929305825280-hkEQ,𝗔 𝘁𝗿𝘂𝗹𝘆 𝘄𝗵𝗼𝗹𝗲𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗡𝗚𝗢 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗻𝘀𝗵𝗶𝗽 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 🌱 As part of our MBA journey, we undertake a mandatory 20-day internship with an affiliated NGO, and honestly, what… | Vaidehi Shah,https://in.linkedin.com/in/vaidehi-shah-47901727a?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image,vaidehi-shah-47901727a,𝗔 𝘁𝗿𝘂𝗹𝘆 𝘄𝗵𝗼𝗹𝗲𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗡𝗚𝗢 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗻𝘀𝗵𝗶𝗽 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 🌱,181,𝗔 𝘁𝗿𝘂𝗹𝘆 𝘄𝗵𝗼𝗹𝗲𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗡𝗚𝗢 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗻𝘀𝗵𝗶𝗽 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 🌱 As part of our MBA journey, we undertake a mandatory 20-day internship with an affiliated NGO, and honestly, what a thoughtful way to give back to society. Kudos to the curators for designing such an intent-driven initiative. I had the opportunity to intern with 𝗦𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗺 𝗕𝗼𝗺𝗯𝗮𝘆 – 𝗗𝗼𝗹𝗽𝗵𝗶𝗻 𝗧𝗮𝗻𝗸𝗶: 𝗔𝗻 𝗶𝗻𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗮𝘁𝗶𝘃𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗯𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗶𝗻𝘃𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗿𝘀 𝗼𝗻 𝗯𝗼𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗱 𝗴𝗿𝗮𝘀𝘀𝗿𝗼𝗼𝘁𝘀 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗿𝗲𝗽𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗲𝘂𝗿𝘀 - 𝗺𝘂𝗰𝗵 𝗹𝗶𝗸𝗲 𝗮 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝘂𝗻𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗱𝗿𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗻 𝗦𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗸 𝗧𝗮𝗻𝗸. Here’s what the experience looked like: • Each of us was assigned 2–3 mentees (aged 16+) who had developed basic skills in domains such as beauty, video editing, photography, bakery, and mobile repair - and were eager to start or scale their own businesses. • Our role was to prepare them for the upcoming funding round by helping them build their pitch decks and understand core business concepts like SWOT, STP, costing, and more. • We also visited their homes in chawls to truly understand their environments, families, and daily realities. Personally, I was clear that I wanted to go beyond just preparing a pitch and so, for the first week, I focused purely on groundwork with my mentees, not even touching the pitch -because skill-building comes first; presentation follows. This meant actively helping them find clients, streamlining their workflows, teaching them how to talk to clients, encouraging deeper technical skill development in their domains, and even working on their grammar - 𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗴𝗼𝗮𝗹: 𝗴𝗿𝗼𝘄𝘁𝗵. You can check out more of their work: https://lnkd.in/eF6wsvfu https://lnkd.in/eYgpy9Ae https://lnkd.in/ey67Nu_e https://lnkd.in/ecUAsStT From day one, my aim was to instill a strong growth mindset and equip them with the tools to pursue it - and I’m proud of the progress we were able to drive together. A big thank you to Gaurav Arora , Gautami Kharat & the entire team for facilitating this and always being there. 𝗜𝗻𝗰𝗿𝗲𝗱𝗶𝗯𝗹𝗲 𝘄𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗿𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗲𝗿𝗴𝘆 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝘂𝗻𝗹𝗼𝗰𝗸. 𝗢𝗻𝘄𝗮𝗿𝗱𝘀 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘂𝗽𝘄𝗮𝗿𝗱𝘀!🚀,post,2026-03-05T06:51:53.508Z,8,2026-02-23T07:36:50.818Z,Person,4,0,𝗔 𝘁𝗿𝘂𝗹𝘆 𝘄𝗵𝗼𝗹𝗲𝘀𝗼𝗺𝗲 𝗡𝗚𝗢 𝗶𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗻𝘀𝗵𝗶𝗽 𝗲𝘅𝗽𝗲𝗿𝗶𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗲 🌱<br/>As part of our MBA journey, we undertake a mandatory 20-day internship with an affiliated NGO, and honestly, what a thoughtful way to give back to society. Kudos to the curators for designing such an intent-driven initiative.<br/><br/>I had the opportunity to intern with 𝗦𝗮𝗹𝗮𝗺 𝗕𝗼𝗺𝗯𝗮𝘆 – 𝗗𝗼𝗹𝗽𝗵𝗶𝗻 𝗧𝗮𝗻𝗸𝗶: 𝗔𝗻 𝗶𝗻𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗮𝘁𝗶𝘃𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗯𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴𝘀 𝗶𝗻𝘃𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗿𝘀 𝗼𝗻 𝗯𝗼𝗮𝗿𝗱 𝘁𝗼 𝗳𝘂𝗻𝗱 𝗴𝗿𝗮𝘀𝘀𝗿𝗼𝗼𝘁𝘀 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗻𝗴 𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗿𝗲𝗽𝗿𝗲𝗻𝗲𝘂𝗿𝘀 - 𝗺𝘂𝗰𝗵 𝗹𝗶𝗸𝗲 𝗮 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝘂𝗻𝗶𝘁𝘆 𝗱𝗿𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗻 𝗦𝗵𝗮𝗿𝗸 𝗧𝗮𝗻𝗸.<br/>Here’s what the experience looked like:<br/><br/>• Each of us was assigned 2–3 mentees (aged 16+) who had developed basic skills in domains such as beauty, video editing, photography, bakery, and mobile repair - and were eager to start or scale their own businesses.<br/>• Our role was to prepare them for the upcoming funding round by helping them build their pitch decks and understand core business concepts like SWOT, STP, costing, and more.<br/>• We also visited their homes in chawls to truly understand their environments, families, and daily realities.<br/>Personally, I was clear that I wanted to go beyond just preparing a pitch and so, for the first week, I focused purely on groundwork with my mentees, not even touching the pitch -because skill-building comes first; presentation follows.<br/>This meant actively helping them find clients, streamlining their workflows, teaching them how to talk to clients, encouraging deeper technical skill development in their domains, and even working on their grammar - 𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗼𝗻𝗲 𝗴𝗼𝗮𝗹: 𝗴𝗿𝗼𝘄𝘁𝗵.<br/><br/>You can check out more of their work:<br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FeF6wsvfu&amp;urlhash=M9LX&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/eF6wsvfu</a><br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FeYgpy9Ae&amp;urlhash=x4l1&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/eYgpy9Ae</a><br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fey67Nu_e&amp;urlhash=Visx&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/ey67Nu_e</a><br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FecUAsStT&amp;urlhash=Tov8&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/ecUAsStT</a><br/><br/>From day one, my aim was to instill a strong growth mindset and equip them with the tools to pursue it - and I’m proud of the progress we were able to drive together. A big thank you to <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/gaurav-arora-071b3317?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Gaurav Arora</a>, <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/gautami-kharat-a19665219?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Gautami Kharat</a> &amp; the entire team for facilitating this and always being there.<br/>𝗜𝗻𝗰𝗿𝗲𝗱𝗶𝗯𝗹𝗲 𝘄𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗿𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 𝘀𝘆𝗻𝗲𝗿𝗴𝘆 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝘂𝗻𝗹𝗼𝗰𝗸.<br/>𝗢𝗻𝘄𝗮𝗿𝗱𝘀 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝘂𝗽𝘄𝗮𝗿𝗱𝘀!🚀,1883,,500,,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D03AQGF5a-7DTjV6w/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B4DZjutL9kHwAg-/0/1756351480491?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=AvtScc2wLL_u62jwLiivuBEYo60J4XrpV3cIYphp31I
neptunejs-game-engine-born-from-challenge-sujal-choudhari,https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/neptunejs-game-engine-born-from-challenge-sujal-choudhari,Neptune.js - The Game Engine Born from a Challenge,https://in.linkedin.com/in/sujalchoudhari,sujalchoudhari,I've always been fascinated by the challenges of creating games within constraints as a game developer. That's why I was intrigued when I heard about the Floppy Disk Game Jam last year.,6,I've always been fascinated by the challenges of creating games within constraints as a game developer. That's why I was intrigued when I heard about the Floppy Disk Game Jam last year. The game jam compelled that the memory size of the game be just under 80kb, that seemed unimaginable at first. Instead of surrendering, I decided to take on the challenge and develop my own game engine that could work within this restrictions. That's how Neptune.js came to be. I started developing Neptune.js on April 5, 2022, and today, almost a year later, I am proud to say that the engine has come a long way. Neptune.js is a set of JavaScript modules specifically designed for writing video games and multimedia programs using the JavaScript language. It adds functionality on top of HTML5 canvas and is highly portable, running on browsers. What sets Neptune.js apart is its minimalist design. The core is simple, and the code is documented neatly, making it easy to use. Even kids can make a simple game in Neptune. The engine is modular, allowing developers to use specific pieces of it separately. Neptune.js is fast and handles the main loop and event cycles under the hood, providing developers with a clean yet customizable feature set. One of the most significant advantages of Neptune.js is its entity component-based system, making it more advanced than previous versions. This system is used by many major engines and provides numerous advantages. Although the learning curve is moderate, the system is worth mastering. During the Floppy Disk Game Jam, I used Neptune.js to create my game, and I am thrilled to say that my game, "Singularity Clicker: Birth of Infinity ," made with Neptune.js, won 3rd prize. The judges were impressed with the game engine, and it even sparked some interest among other developers in the game jam. As we approach the one-year mark of Neptune.js's development, I am excited to see what the future holds for this game engine. I am constantly working to improve Neptune.js and adding new features to make it an even more powerful tool for game developers. #gamejam #gamedevelopment #javascript #minimalistdesign #modular #opensource #videogames #multimedia #programming #tech #innovation,article,2026-03-05T06:51:53.702Z,,2023-04-05T04:30:01.000Z,Person,0,,<br/>        <p><br/>          <span class>I&apos;ve always been fascinated by the challenges of creating games within constraints as a game developer. That&apos;s why I was intrigued when I heard about the </span><span class><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Fneptune-js%2Evercel%2Eapp%2F&amp;urlhash=NkkE&amp;trk=article-ssr-frontend-pulse_little-text-block" target="_blank" data-tracking-control-name="article-ssr-frontend-pulse_little-text-block" data-tracking-will-navigate data-test-link>Floppy Disk Game Jam<!----></a></span><span class> last year. The game jam compelled that the memory size of the game be just under 80kb, that seemed unimaginable at first. Instead of surrendering, I decided to take on the challenge and develop my own game engine that could work within this restrictions. That&apos;s how </span><span class><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Fneptune-js%2Evercel%2Eapp%2F&amp;urlhash=NkkE&amp;trk=article-ssr-frontend-pulse_little-text-block" target="_blank" data-tracking-control-name="article-ssr-frontend-pulse_little-text-block" data-tracking-will-navigate data-test-link>Neptune.js<!----></a></span><span class> came to be.</span><!----><br/>        </p><br/>    ,4975,,500,,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5603AQG1HPT6yzJGsw/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B56ZpE.z8wKEAg-/0/1762093912827?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=1GGO0GtYSjh3G5ieW2KSDF82vfQUAjIOwNnW19Sxfkg
7432437501581000705,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/mohitnippanikar_hackathon-building-mentor-activity-7432437501581000705-VW2K,#hackathon #building #mentor | Mohit Nippanikar | 23 comments,https://in.linkedin.com/in/mohitnippanikar?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image,mohitnippanikar,𝐌𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐨𝐫.,270,𝐌𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐨𝐫. 𝐓𝐡𝐚𝐭'𝐬 𝐰𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐯𝐢𝐭𝐞 𝐬𝐚𝐢𝐝. I wasn't sure I earned it yet. Still learning. prepping for placements. Still building my startup. Still keeping up with the latest tech. I'm not done being a student. But Umar Khan called anyway. "w𝘦 𝘸𝘢𝘯𝘵 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘢𝘴 𝘢 𝘔𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘰𝘳." Same room. Same energy. Different chair. And that changed everything. I chose FinTech. My domain. My battleground for 2 years. Alongside Manav Shah , we sat across 11 teams. 5-10 minutes each. But before I entered that room? 𝐈 𝐝𝐢𝐝 𝐦𝐲 𝐡𝐨𝐦𝐞𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤. Read every problem statement like I was building it myself. Mapped existing competitors. Identified market gaps. Figured out what the best possible product could look like. Before they even pitched. Because that's what an ideal mentor owes every team. Not just opinions. Not just motivation. Real preparation. Then I learned the hardest part. 𝐋𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠. Some teams were brilliant but scattered. Some were confident but solving the wrong problem. Some were raw but asking questions that made me rethink my own approach. And here's what nobody tells you about mentoring.. Every team shared their idea with me in trust. Their MVP. Their pitch angle. Their secret edge. And I kept every single one. I didn't compare Team A to Team B. A mentor doesn't leak. A mentor protects the room they've been given. Guided them on.. What do the judges want to see? What does the user actually need? What does your idea solve that no one else can? Not my answers. Theirs refined through the right questions. That's the difference between giving direction and building clarity. Here's the truth about mentoring: Competing is about controlling your execution. Building your solution. Fixing your bugs. Winning your pitch. Mentoring? You control nothing. You guide. You suggest. You nudge. You hope they see what you're pointing at. Because somewhere between guiding teams.. I stopped being just a competitor. I became a builder of competitors. And honestly? 𝘛𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘮𝘪𝘨𝘩𝘵 𝘣𝘦 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘣𝘪𝘨𝘨𝘦𝘴𝘵 𝘸𝘪𝘯 𝘰𝘧 𝘮𝘺 𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘪𝘳𝘦 𝘩𝘢𝘤𝘬𝘢𝘵𝘩𝘰𝘯 𝘫𝘰𝘶𝘳𝘯𝘦𝘺. Grateful to be back to Shri Bhagubhai Mafatlal Polytechnic !!! — Mohit Nippanikar | curious enough to break things across every field #Hackathon #Building #Mentor,post,2026-03-05T06:51:54.928Z,16,2026-02-25T14:53:08.366Z,Person,23,0,𝐌𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐨𝐫. 𝐓𝐡𝐚𝐭&apos;𝐬 𝐰𝐡𝐚𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐢𝐧𝐯𝐢𝐭𝐞 𝐬𝐚𝐢𝐝. I wasn&apos;t sure I earned it yet.<br/><br/>Still learning. prepping for placements. <br/>Still building my startup. <br/>Still keeping up with the latest tech.<br/><br/>I&apos;m not done being a student.<br/><br/>But Umar Khan called anyway.<br/>&quot;w𝘦 𝘸𝘢𝘯𝘵 𝘺𝘰𝘶 𝘢𝘴 𝘢 𝘔𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘰𝘳.&quot;<br/><br/>Same room. Same energy. Different chair.<br/>And that changed everything.<br/><br/><br/><br/>I chose FinTech. My domain. My battleground for 2 years.<br/><br/>Alongside <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/manav-shah-a711911b6?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Manav Shah</a>, we sat across 11 teams. 5-10 minutes each. <br/><br/><br/><br/>But before I entered that room? 𝐈 𝐝𝐢𝐝 𝐦𝐲 𝐡𝐨𝐦𝐞𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤.<br/><br/>Read every problem statement like I was building it myself. <br/>Mapped existing competitors.<br/>Identified market gaps. <br/>Figured out what the best possible product could look like.<br/><br/>Before they even pitched.<br/>Because that&apos;s what an ideal mentor owes every team. Not just opinions. Not just motivation.<br/>Real preparation.<br/><br/><br/><br/>Then I learned the hardest part. 𝐋𝐢𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐧𝐢𝐧𝐠.<br/><br/>Some teams were brilliant but scattered. <br/>Some were confident but solving the wrong problem. <br/>Some were raw but asking questions that made me rethink my own approach.<br/><br/><br/>And here&apos;s what nobody tells you about mentoring..<br/><br/>Every team shared their idea with me in trust. <br/>Their MVP. <br/>Their pitch angle. <br/>Their secret edge.<br/>And I kept every single one.<br/><br/>I didn&apos;t compare Team A to Team B.<br/>A mentor doesn&apos;t leak. <br/>A mentor protects the room they&apos;ve been given.<br/><br/><br/><br/>Guided them on..<br/>What do the judges want to see? What does the user actually need? What does your idea solve that no one else can?<br/><br/>Not my answers. Theirs refined through the right questions.<br/>That&apos;s the difference between giving direction and building clarity.<br/><br/><br/><br/>Here&apos;s the truth about mentoring:<br/>Competing is about controlling your execution. <br/>Building your solution. <br/>Fixing your bugs. <br/>Winning your pitch.<br/>Mentoring? You control nothing.<br/><br/>You guide. You suggest. You nudge. <br/>You hope they see what you&apos;re pointing at.<br/><br/><br/><br/>Because somewhere between guiding teams..<br/>I stopped being just a competitor.<br/>I became a builder of competitors.<br/>And honestly?<br/><br/>𝘛𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘮𝘪𝘨𝘩𝘵 𝘣𝘦 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘣𝘪𝘨𝘨𝘦𝘴𝘵 𝘸𝘪𝘯 𝘰𝘧 𝘮𝘺 𝘦𝘯𝘵𝘪𝘳𝘦 𝘩𝘢𝘤𝘬𝘢𝘵𝘩𝘰𝘯 𝘫𝘰𝘶𝘳𝘯𝘦𝘺.<br/><br/><br/>Grateful to be back to <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/shri-bhagubhai-mafatlal-polytechnic-06261a1a3?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Shri Bhagubhai Mafatlal Polytechnic</a>!!!<br/><br/>— <a class="link" href="https://in.linkedin.com/in/mohitnippanikar?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Mohit Nippanikar</a> | curious enough to break things across every field<br/><br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fhackathon&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#Hackathon</a> <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fbuilding&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#Building</a> <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fmentor&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#Mentor</a>,2947,,500,,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D03AQGRGsW8TJAGzA/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B4DZt5_k0ZKQAg-/0/1767278271384?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=LO3n0f9ucDpuWlXQ6sMYbmV-zYDoDEFY9AJQgVv60Uo
7431861605900111872,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/ayaangazali_we-just-won-120000-at-the-y-combinator-activity-7431861605900111872-c0rS,We just won $120,000 at the Y Combinator Hackathon This now makes me the youngest person ever to place 1st overall at a YC hackathon (age: 18). Shoutout to my team Hrishikesh Athreya, Arnav D.… | Ayaan Gazali | 351 comments,https://www.linkedin.com/in/ayaangazali,ayaangazali,We just won $120,000 at the Y Combinator Hackathon,1634,We just won $120,000 at the Y Combinator Hackathon This now makes me the youngest person ever to place 1st overall at a YC hackathon (age: 18). Shoutout to my team Hrishikesh Athreya , Arnav D. , and Aditi Apoorva Jagalur Raghuvara (from SCU). We built Vital Link using OpenAI, Manufact, and Cloudflare, by integrating health data from different personal devices onto ChatGPT securely. Between us, we have a combined 55 hackathon wins (some overlapping), and we used all of that experience to execute fast under pressure. In the end, we walked away with: • $120,000 in prizes • a YC interview with a General Partner (upcoming batch) What people don’t see is that I’ve lost 9 YC hackathons before this and only won 2nd (track prize). This one means a lot. Huge shoutout to the sponsors for making this event incredible and the prize pool so big Manufact (formerly mcp-use) , OpenAI , Cloudflare , Puzzle , and of course the YC General Partner.,post,2026-03-05T06:51:54.982Z,49,2026-02-24T00:44:44.135Z,Person,351,0,We just won $120,000 at the <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/school/y-combinator/?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Y Combinator</a> Hackathon<br/><br/><br/>This now makes me the youngest person ever to place 1st overall at a YC hackathon (age: 18).<br/><br/>Shoutout to my team <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/hrishikesh-athreya?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Hrishikesh Athreya</a>, <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/arnavdewan?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Arnav D.</a>, and <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/aditi-apoorva-jagalur-raghuvara-53895a1a7?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Aditi Apoorva Jagalur Raghuvara</a> (from SCU). We built Vital Link using OpenAI, Manufact, and Cloudflare, by integrating health data from different personal devices onto ChatGPT securely.<br/><br/>Between us, we have a combined 55 hackathon wins (some overlapping), and we used all of that experience to execute fast under pressure.<br/><br/>In the end, we walked away with:<br/>	•	$120,000 in prizes<br/>	•	a YC interview with a General Partner (upcoming batch)<br/><br/>What people don’t see is that I’ve lost 9 YC hackathons before this and only won 2nd (track prize).<br/><br/>This one means a lot.<br/><br/>Huge shoutout to the sponsors for making this event incredible and the prize pool so big <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/mcp-use?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Manufact (formerly mcp-use)</a>, <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/openai?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>OpenAI</a>, <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/cloudflare?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Cloudflare</a>, <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/puzzlefin?trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>Puzzle</a> , and of course the YC General Partner.,4819,93,500,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D5605AQFcH6QTYc1zaw/feedshare-thumbnail_720_1280/B56ZyNGq5yKkA8-/0/1771893865933?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=9zrEgzUkmO3cZwuP4jspNpb6bv_zSQLaano_Zyb0_-A,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4D03AQE2R0BI9-HCPg/profile-displayphoto-scale_400_400/B4DZq0lUm2GkAg-/0/1763966274998?e=2147483647&v=beta&t=Nf6eIWR2DVdYYbSYonf5WHsfrnCFSgTp8kO0z2zUrDE
7430692892538552320,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/kshitijaucharmal21_gamedev-graphicsprogramming-indiedev-activity-7430692892538552320-saSW,Building ConceptForge: Custom Real-Time Game Engine in C++ with OpenGL | Kshitij Aucharmal posted on the topic | LinkedIn,https://in.linkedin.com/in/kshitijaucharmal21,kshitijaucharmal21,Building my own game engine from scratch — and it's starting to feel alive.,221,Building my own game engine from scratch — and it's starting to feel alive. ConceptForge is a custom real-time engine I'm creating in C++ with OpenGL. It uses an ECS architecture (Entity-Component-System) — a flexible way to build game objects by mixing reusable pieces (like position, light, or model) instead of rigid classes. This makes everything faster and easier to extend. Plus, Python scripting is baked in, so eventually you can just describe what you want in plain English and have AI help generate it. This month I pushed hard: - Revived the in-engine editor with a live Python code runner (hit Run → see "Hello World" + time print instantly) - Added proper scene hierarchy (drag objects to parent them, move lights around a cathedral) - Implemented advanced graphics tricks: depth & stencil buffers for clean outlines, a cool toon shader for stylized looks, antialiasing, and full shadow mapping (with soft edges via PCF filtering — tested on a detailed backpack model) Videos attached show the progress: orbiting lights casting real shadows, smooth borders, hierarchy in action. 121 commits total. Still early days, but the foundation is solid and fun to build on. I post daily on my X account: https://x.com/ma_at_anubis With devlogs here: https://lnkd.in/eZFxzqWa Repo here if you're curious: https://lnkd.in/eYSNmcw9 Thoughts on ECS engines, shadows, or AI integration? Would love to hear them. #GameDev #GraphicsProgramming #IndieDev #Cpp #OpenGL #ConceptForge,post,2026-03-05T06:51:59.649Z,21,2026-02-20T19:20:41.161Z,Person,28,0,Building my own game engine from scratch — and it&apos;s starting to feel alive. <br/><br/>ConceptForge is a custom real-time engine I&apos;m creating in C++ with OpenGL. It uses an ECS architecture (Entity-Component-System) — a flexible way to build game objects by mixing reusable pieces (like position, light, or model) instead of rigid classes. This makes everything faster and easier to extend. <br/><br/>Plus, Python scripting is baked in, so eventually you can just describe what you want in plain English and have AI help generate it. <br/>This month I pushed hard: <br/>- Revived the in-engine editor with a live Python code runner (hit Run → see &quot;Hello World&quot; + time print instantly) <br/>- Added proper scene hierarchy (drag objects to parent them, move lights around a cathedral) <br/>- Implemented advanced graphics tricks: depth &amp; stencil buffers for clean outlines, a cool toon shader for stylized looks, antialiasing, and full shadow mapping (with soft edges via PCF filtering — tested on a detailed backpack model)<br/><br/>Videos attached show the progress: orbiting lights casting real shadows, smooth borders, hierarchy in action. <br/><br/>121 commits total. Still early days, but the foundation is solid and fun to build on. <br/><br/>I post daily on my X account: <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Fx%2Ecom%2Fma_at_anubis&amp;urlhash=4Ez3&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://x.com/ma_at_anubis</a><br/>With devlogs here: <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FeZFxzqWa&amp;urlhash=Oa7r&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/eZFxzqWa</a><br/><br/>Repo here if you&apos;re curious: <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FeYSNmcw9&amp;urlhash=6nY4&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" rel="nofollow" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>https://lnkd.in/eYSNmcw9</a> <br/><br/>Thoughts on ECS engines, shadows, or AI integration? <br/>Would love to hear them. <br/> <br/><a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fgamedev&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#GameDev</a> <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fgraphicsprogramming&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#GraphicsProgramming</a> <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Findiedev&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#IndieDev</a> <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fcpp&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#Cpp</a> <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fopengl&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#OpenGL</a> <a class="link" href="https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fconceptforge&amp;trk=public_post-text" target="_self" data-tracking-control-name="public_post-text" data-tracking-will-navigate>#ConceptForge</a>,886,29,500,https://media.licdn.com/dms/image/v2/D4E05AQFkQdXrV8UifA/videocover-high/B4EZx8fxw6JsBY-/0/17716152