,,7431097292121853952,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/eyad-tawfik_houdini-sidefx-technicalart-activity-7431097292121853952-T85B,eyad-tawfik,["#Houdini","#SideFX","#TechnicalArt","#VFX","#ClaudeAI","#MCP","#Pipeline","#VEX"],,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/eyad-tawfik_houdini-sidefx-technicalart-activity-7431097292121853952-T85B,16,I’ve spent this morning getting a simple MCP bridge for Houdini sorted on my local machine. I like seeing these sort of use cases for language models in VFX, though I reckon there’s still a healthy gap between a flashy demo and a production ready workflow. The advantage at the moment is definitely VEX and Python automation. Having an LLM that’s actually context-aware of the live session is a massive help for the logic side of things. It's a genuine workflow boost for generating snippets on the fly. That said, you do still need to keep a close eye on it when it comes to actual scene architecture. Like in the video below, I was testing a simple particle setup and Claude decided to get a bit over-excited, it wired in a redunant collision node and overcomplicated a simple rule setup that could be done with one wrangle. It’s brilliant at the code, but it’s still prone to over egging the pudding on the layout side. Very handy tool to have in the arsenal for scripting and prototyping, provided you’re there to tidy up after it. I have seen some plugins and tools like an AI Assistant for Houdini with keys to use many other LLMs, would love to hear from people who have used it and if there are any benefits to it compared to connecting specific language models with an MCP #Houdini #SideFX #TechnicalArt #VFX #ClaudeAI #MCP #Pipeline #VEX,2026-02-21T22:07:37.553Z,1,["https://x.com/ma_at_anubis","https://lnkd.in/eZFxzqWa","https://lnkd.in/eYSNmcw9","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/gamedev","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/graphicsprogramming","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/indiedev","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/cpp","https:/