,,7427230414487904256,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/rasmivan-ilangovan_scala-functionalprogramming-softwareengineering-activity-7427230414487904256-IUtx,rasmivan-ilangovan,["#Scala","#FunctionalProgramming","#SoftwareEngineering","#RiveApp","#DataVisualization","#LearningInPublic","#JVM","#Coding"],,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/rasmivan-ilangovan_scala-functionalprogramming-softwareengineering-activity-7427230414487904256-IUtx,8,Visualising Scala: The Mechanics of a .map 🧬 Following up on my S3 Glacier animation, I wanted to apply the same visual logic to a core functional programming concept: the Scala map function. In Scala, map is more than just a loop; it’s a transformation that yields a brand-new collection while leaving the original data untouched. What’s happening in this Rive animation? 📥 The Input: We start with an immutable collection of integers. ⚙️ The Transformation: Each element passes through the transformer function f(x) = 10 * x. 📤 The Result: A new collection is produced with the transformed values. Building these visualisations is helping me bridge the gap between high-level system architecture and low-level code logic. #Scala #FunctionalProgramming #SoftwareEngineering #RiveApp #DataVisualization #LearningInPublic #JVM #Coding,2026-02-11T06:02:02.082Z,0,["https://x.com/ma_at_anubis","https://lnkd.in/eZFxzqWa","https://lnkd.in/eYSNmcw9","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/gamedev","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/graphicsprogramming","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/indiedev","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/cpp","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/opengl","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/conceptforge","http://menu.py/","http://importlib.reload/?trk=public_post-text","http://nuke.menu/","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/vfxstudio","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/animationstudioes","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/python","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/nuke","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/h