laudeai","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/mcp","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/pipeline","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/vex","https://www.linkedin.com/company/rive-app?trk=public_post-text","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/scala","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/functionalprogramming","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/softwareengineering","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/riveapp","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/datavisualization","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/learninginpublic","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/jvm","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/coding","https://lnkd.in/g5NPk44D","https://lnkd.in/gnfXJ-yu","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/python","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/pygame","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/gamedevelopment","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/algorithms","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/astar","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/softwaredevelopment","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/coding","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/projects","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/csuf","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/algorithmengineering","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/spring2026","https://lnkd.in/eHjymfzg","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/codex","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/claudecode","https://lnkd.in/euWRjrUa"]
,,7429327886974824448,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/janusalexandersantos_csuf-algorithmengineering-spring2026-activity-7429327886974824448-E1vJ,janusalexandersantos,["#CSUF","#AlgorithmEngineering","#Spring2026"],,https://www.linkedin.com/posts/janusalexandersantos_csuf-algorithmengineering-spring2026-activity-7429327886974824448-E1vJ,0,My team and I built a Sorting Algorithm Visualizer using Python and Pygame for my CS335 course — and it turned out to be one of the more rewarding projects I've worked on. The idea is straightforward: instead of just reading about how sorting algorithms work, you can actually watch them in action. The app renders arrays as color-coded bars and animates each comparison, swap, and merge in real time, making it easy to see the differences between algorithms. What's included: 5 sorting algorithms: Bubble Sort, Insertion Sort, Merge Sort, Quick Sort, and Radix Sort Linear Search visualization Color-coded animation — green for the current position, red for comparisons and swaps Ascending and descending sort toggle with adjustable array sizes from 5 to 100 elements UI with custom-built interactive components On the technical side: Used Python's generator pattern to pause algorithms mid-execution, enabling frame-by-frame animation without multithreading Kept the architecture modular — configuration, algorithms, UI, and rendering each live in their own dedicated modules Pygame handles all the rendering at a consistent 60 FPS Working through this gave me a stronger grasp of algorithm complexity and reinforced solid habits around code organization and separation of concerns. Watching Radix Sort do its thing never gets old. #CSUF #AlgorithmEngineering #Spring2026,2026-02-17T00:56:38.492Z,0,["https://x.com/ma_at_anubis","https://lnkd.in/eZFxzqWa","https://lnkd.in/eYSNmcw9","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/gamedev","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/graphicsprogramming","https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/indiedev","https://www.linke