How does it solve context window problem? You feed it with year long memories and expect it to follow up on something you discussed 8 months ago. How would that fit into 128k context window (practical limit for most models today)? Even if you had a database solution, how would your conversation hit the 8 months ago memory and follow up on that? In a real conversation, you expect someone to randomly just remember something from past and bring tha topic up, just like how your agent asked about the progress about your project. Since your project comes in the most recent memory and probably within the model context it works. Would you expect it to work for the above scenario? Example - Your friend suddenly remembered discussing about doing a side gig together, a few months ago and asks you if you’re still up for it.,https://in.linkedin.com/in/venusaim000?trk=public_post_comment_actor-name,venusaim000,Venu Sai Madisetti,,2026-03-02T06:33:59.367Z,,6,
this is such a strong move. building and shipping a deep integration while sponsoring a yc hackathon is elite execution. voice agents without memory always feel shallow, and solving that with almost instant latency and user profiles is a real unlock. love how focused supermemory is becoming on being the infrastructure layer agents actually need. this is the kind of quiet upgrade that makes the whole ecosystem better.,https://in.linkedin.com/in/rishul-chanana?trk=public_post_comment_actor-name,rishul-chanana,Rishul Chanana,,2026-03-01T16:07:15.248Z,,0,
